Unconverted long-term prisoners praised
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, August 26 (KCNA) -- The world public is highly praising the unconverted long-term prisoners in South Korea, who have fought unyieldingly for scores of years behind bars, true to the vow made to the fatherland and the revolution, as men of strong faith and will. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The secretary general of the executive secretariat of the organization of solidarity of the peoples of Asia, Africa and Latin America in a letter to the president of the UN Commission on Human Rights said that he highly praised and respected the unconverted long-term prisoners who are boundlessly loyal to their fatherland and people and have firm faith. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The Peruvian Committee for Supporting the Independent and Peaceful Reunification of Korea, the Italian Committee for the Reunification and Peace of Korea, the Ugandan Railway Workers' Federation and the All-India Agricultural Workers Union separately issued statements. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The Mexican Fellowship Union to Honor the Memory of President Kim Il Sung, the Mexican Committee for Supporting Korea's Reunification and the Mexico-DPRK Friendship and Cultural Exchange Association issued a joint statement, and the chairman of the Austrian Committee to Support Korea's Reunification made public a statement. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Recalling that an "ideological conversion" was imposed upon the unconverted long-term prisoners and they were put to brutal torture for scores of years behind bars and they have been subjected to unbearable mental and physical harassment in the subsequent period, too, after being defined as "those under supervision for public peace," they stressed that though belatedly, they should be allowed to spend the remaining years of their lives in their hometowns at the earliest possible date where their parents, brothers and sisters, wives and children are awaiting them.
